<dl id="n10033d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10033d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10033d"> 33(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ quadriga ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10033d"><li>FW 486.05 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n10033d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n10033d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10033d">MS BL 47482b-70</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:019 <a name="rA1yd" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rA1yd">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/r/rA1yd.htm#n10033d">Draft: III&sect;3A.1+</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Les chars de courses (<i>currus, curriculum</i>), qui &eacute;taient appel&eacute;s selon l&apos;attelage <i>Biga, Triga</i> ou <i>Quadriga</i> et qui &eacute;taient d&apos;une construction tr&egrave;s l&eacute;g&egrave;re, avec des roues tr&egrave;s basses et un char de triomphe (<i>currus triumphalis</i>), nous montrent encore d&apos;autres v&eacute;hicules romains &agrave; deux roues. <font color="green">[Race chariots (currus, curriculum) were named, according to the number of horses they had, Biga, Triga, or Quadriga. They were very light and had their wheels set very low. Along with the triumphal chariot (currus triumphalis) they show us yet more two-wheeled Roman vehicles.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 31</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
